00:22:56.719 --> 00:23:06.640
area that you, that you think you enjoy and then keep bridging that statistician to ML,

00:23:06.640 --> 00:23:13.839
like I'm talking about optimization to AI and ML, because I still think that in some of the,

00:23:14.400 --> 00:23:20.160
some of the areas you, machine learning starts with a lot of data and then you put some algorithms

00:23:20.160 --> 00:23:26.959
and it infers some models to it. That's basically what it does. Things like integer programming

00:23:27.520 --> 00:23:33.599
starts with a model of the process. And there are so many things that, that we can do with

00:23:33.599 --> 00:23:39.760
a model of the process rather than starting from scratch each time. And in an example in

00:23:39.760 --> 00:23:49.920
reinforcement learning is you're teaching a car to drive itself. Then as a human, we, we implicitly

00:23:49.920 --> 00:23:56.560
know things like, Hey, if I learned that I'm turning the steering wheel left and the car does

00:23:56.560 --> 00:24:02.640
this, then our model, our brain has this model of symmetry that says, basically I can do the

00:24:02.640 --> 00:24:09.119
same thing when I'm turning to the right. But just a standard reinforcement learning algorithm

00:24:09.119 --> 00:24:14.400
doesn't have that built in symmetry. So you can even put, infuse some models of

00:24:14.959 --> 00:24:21.359
gravitation or symmetry and things like that, even into reinforcement learning. So, you know,

00:24:21.359 --> 00:24:29.520
that's my, my thoughts on those is that you have a, find what you really enjoy doing. And,

00:24:29.920 --> 00:24:34.319
