00:24:46.160 --> 00:24:52.479
Warren, a question I wanted to ask you is, is thinking back over all the different roles you

00:24:52.479 --> 00:24:56.880
have, is there a project that comes to mind that you're most proud of in your career?

00:24:57.439 --> 00:25:06.239
Well, there's a few, you know, the, the, there's a couple, one, one is an optimization project at

00:25:06.239 --> 00:25:14.079
Lucent that the, so we've, we've heard the, we've heard the famous saying, and I can't remember

00:25:14.079 --> 00:25:22.880
who said it, all models are wrong. Some models are useful. So there was this integer programming

00:25:23.599 --> 00:25:32.319
model that assigned raw materials to the cables. And at the time, the, these, the, the cables were

00:25:32.319 --> 00:25:39.599
made of stacks of ribbons of fiber, so they could be up to 864 fibers in a cable. And the pressure

00:25:39.599 --> 00:25:47.520
on the sides of a circular cable on this, this rectangular stack caused issues on, on the edges.

00:25:47.520 --> 00:25:54.479
And so we call them edge ribbons or corner ribbons. And, and for a while there, you wanted

00:25:54.479 --> 00:25:58.719
to, you didn't have enough of that really good fiber. So you had to do it a specific,

00:25:59.520 --> 00:26:06.479
you had to really allocate it the right way. Then a few months later, well, maybe a year later,

00:26:07.280 --> 00:26:12.239
our factory processes had gotten so much better that we just had way too much of this. And we

00:26:12.239 --> 00:26:18.880
were trying to, to keep it separate. And then we started to not be able to give out orders or

00:26:18.880 --> 00:26:25.280
complete orders because, because we were taking this premium fiber and never using it. And

00:26:26.719 --> 00:26:33.760
some of us got together, got on a whiteboard and found out that there, if you took this substitution

00:26:33.760 --> 00:26:38.880
matrix of what five, what ribbons could substitute for each other, like this one's better than this

00:26:38.880 --> 00:26:46.719
one. So it could substitute for the other one. And you put that, that matrix in there as a, a

00:26:46.719 --> 00:26:54.160
minimum and the transpose of that matrix as the maximum, then all of a sudden, just, just by adding

00:26:54.160 --> 00:27:01.119
those two matrices in there, everything could substitute for each other. And we were able to

00:27:01.599 --> 00:27:10.479
increase the capacity of the factory and reduce waste. And it was all because, you know, we got

00:27:10.479 --> 00:27:16.079
together and we were, and we used, you know, a couple of mathematical ideas. So I think that's

00:27:16.079 --> 00:27:24.000
the, that's the big optimization one. And then the one where sometimes it's a, just a conversation

00:27:24.000 --> 00:27:30.000
or something that you read, there was at UPS, there was this idea that you, that you used

00:27:31.439 --> 00:27:38.000
yeses and nos on the bids that you sent out to your clients, your big commercial clients,

00:27:38.000 --> 00:27:44.000
if they said you would give them, we'll give you 10% off retail rate and they'd say either yes or

00:27:44.000 --> 00:27:51.839
no. And you get this, you get tens of thousands of these data points and you create this, this

00:27:51.839 --> 00:27:58.319
logistic regression that can give you an idea of what your competitors are charging, because you

00:27:58.319 --> 00:28:03.839
think that everybody's rational. If UPS gives you 10% and they turn it down, then likely FedEx or

00:28:03.839 --> 00:28:12.719
somebody else gave them an 11 or 12. Well, the, the amount of the, the numbers coming out were,

00:28:13.439 --> 00:28:18.640
the results coming out were good, but they didn't make, you couldn't explain them. And it turns out

00:28:19.599 --> 00:28:24.319
that it was because of the data that was coming in. It was basically censored. It was,

00:28:24.319 --> 00:28:28.000
you didn't, you didn't ask them, I'll give you zero. And they say, no, I'll give you one. They

00:28:28.000 --> 00:28:34.400
say, no, I'll give you two. They say no. And then finally you get to 10. You got all these data

00:28:34.400 --> 00:28:41.520
points right around the, the answers. So without, now I'm realizing that I'm saying something that

00:28:41.520 --> 00:28:47.760
I'm not, not actually showing you on a graph, but make long story short, I read something in a paper

00:28:47.839 --> 00:28:55.199
where somebody called them shadow data points or mirror data points. And we infused the actual data

00:28:55.199 --> 00:29:02.959
set with we said, if you, if you accept it at 10%, then you would have accepted at 11 or 12 or 13.

00:29:02.959 --> 00:29:07.839
And we put all of those in. And if you, if you turn this down at 10%, then you would have turned

00:29:07.839 --> 00:29:12.479
us down at nine, eight, seven, six, five, four, three, two, one. And when we put all of these

00:29:12.479 --> 00:29:19.920
data points in there, everything worked and you could explain it. And we put a, we, we,

00:29:19.920 --> 00:29:26.560
we actually patented that idea that you could infuse data sets in this particular application

00:29:27.920 --> 00:29:34.640
with what we call shadow data points. So sometimes it's, you know, you can, you can

00:29:34.640 --> 00:29:39.920
augment your data set with successes and failures that weren't really there because you think that

00:29:39.920 --> 00:29:45.280
a rational person would, if they're going to accept at a certain price, they would certainly

00:29:45.280 --> 00:29:49.119
accept at a less price, or they're going to turn you down at a certain price. They're going to turn

00:29:49.119 --> 00:29:54.800
you down at a higher price. So that was a really interesting thing that worked for UPS. I saw

00:29:54.800 --> 00:30:00.479
somebody at a, at a conference that they were in hotels. They, they described the same problem.

00:30:00.479 --> 00:30:06.479
And I said, since you're in hotels and you're not competing with UPS, here's, here's our solution.

00:30:06.959 --> 00:30:09.760
And, and it worked for them as well. So.

